'''Bukayo Ayoyinka Temidayo Moses Saka''' ({{Audio|Bukayo_Ayoyinka_Temidayo_Saka.wav|listen}}, born 5 September 2001) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[right winger]] for {{English football updater|Arsenal}} club [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]].

Saka has spent the entirety of his [[First team (association football)|first-team]] club career with Arsenal, where he has won the Premier League, an [[FA Cup]] and two [[FA Community Shield]]s, progressively becoming one of Arsenal's most influential players.<ref>{{Cite web |date=26 December 2021 |title=Opinion: Bukayo Saka and Emile Smith Rowe have taken their game to the next level as Arsenal continue rise |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/premier-league/2021-2022/opinion-bukayo-saka-and-emile-smith-rowe-have-taken-their-game-to-the-next-level-as-arsenal-continue_sto8684604/story.shtml |access-date=3 January 2022 |website=Eurosport |archive-date=29 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230629094728/https://www.eurosport.com/geoblocking.shtml |url-status=live }}</ref> Following both the [[2020–21 Arsenal F.C. season|2020–21]] and [[2021–22 Arsenal F.C. season|2021–22]] seasons, he was named as [[Arsenal Player of the Season|Arsenal's Player of the Season]].

Saka represented England at various youth levels before making his debut for the senior team in October 2020. He was part of England's squads for [[UEFA Euro 2020]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024]], which England finished as runners-up in both, the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] and the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].

==Early life==
Bukayo Ayoyinka Temidayo Moses Saka<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersS/BioSakaB.html |title=Bukayo Saka |website=England Football Online |publisher=Chris Goodwin and Glen Isherwood |date=20 February 2026 |access-date=21 February 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230605175440/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/TeamPlyrsBios/PlayersS/BioSakaB.html |archive-date=5 June 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> was born on 5 September 2001<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/player/_/id/280555/bukayo-saka |title=Bukayo Saka: Overview |publisher=ESPN |access-date=10 October 2020 |archive-date=23 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210523175248/https://www.espn.co.uk/football/player/_/id/280555/bukayo-saka |url-status=live }}</ref> in [[Ealing]], Greater London, to [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] Nigerian parents, Adenike and Yomi Saka,<ref>{{cite news |date=27 June 2021 |title=BUKAYO SAKA: From family home to N1.2b luxury pad The Nation Newspaper |newspaper=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation]]|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/bukayo-saka-from-family-home-to-n1-2b-luxury-pad/ |location=Lagos, Nigeria|access-date=22 October 2022 |archive-date=22 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221022134954/https://thenationonlineng.net/bukayo-saka-from-family-home-to-n1-2b-luxury-pad/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Oludare |first=Shina |date=8 July 2020 |title=Saka: Ikpeba wants Arsenal star invited to Super Eagles |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/saka-ikpeba-wants-arsenal-star-invited-to-super-eagles/rdqdxsri9z121n2nunolxsg9d |access-date=18 October 2020 |website=Goal |publisher=Perform Group |archive-date=18 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201018214558/https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/saka-ikpeba-wants-arsenal-star-invited-to-super-eagles/rdqdxsri9z121n2nunolxsg9d |url-status=live }}</ref> the younger of two children. His parents emigrated to London from Nigeria as economic migrants.<ref>{{cite web |date=24 July 2020 |title=10 things you may not know about Bukayo Saka – Arsenal's new number 7 |url=https://www.givemesport.com/1585380-bukayo-saka-10-things-you-may-not-know-about-arsenals-breakthrough-star |access-date=28 January 2021 |website=GiveMeSport |archive-date=9 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109210741/https://www.givemesport.com/1585380-bukayo-saka-10-things-you-may-not-know-about-arsenals-breakthrough-star |url-status=live }}</ref> He attended Edward Betham Church of England Primary School<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edwardbetham.ealing.sch.uk/pdfs/letters/HT%20letters/2018-19/Issue%2033%20-%2017th%20June%202019.pdf |title=Issue 33 – 17th June 2019 |publisher=The Edward Betham C of E Primary School |access-date=2 December 2021 |archive-date=27 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211127024618/https://www.edwardbetham.ealing.sch.uk/pdfs/letters/HT%20letters/2018-19/Issue%2033%20-%2017th%20June%202019.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> before [[Greenford High School]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Watts |first1=Charles |last2=Clementine |first2=Katherine |date=13 December 2018 |title=Arsenal FC's Bukayo Saka: The young Ealing-born player making his senior debut |url=https://www.mylondon.news/sport/football/arsenal-fcs-bukayo-saka-young-15549899 |access-date=21 February 2020 |website=MyLondon |publisher=Reach |archive-date=30 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201130053420/https://www.mylondon.news/sport/football/arsenal-fcs-bukayo-saka-young-15549899 |url-status=live }}</ref> where he gained high grades in his [[GCSE]]s, achieving four A*s and three As.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ellery |first=Ben |title=England star Bukayo Saka was a real role model, says PE teacher |newspaper=[[The Times]] |url=https://www.thetimes.com/article/england-star-bukayo-saka-was-a-real-role-model-says-pe-teacher-fchh85nlq |url-access=subscription |access-date=26 July 2021 |archive-date=26 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210726202417/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/england-star-bukayo-saka-was-a-real-role-model-says-pe-teacher-fchh85nlq |url-status=live }}</ref> Prior to joining [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], Saka played youth football for local club Greenford Celtic.<ref>{{cite news |title='I'm crying writing this': Final good luck messages for England's stars – by those who know them best |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/euro-2021/2021/07/09/crying-writing-final-good-luck-messages-englands-stars-know/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/euro-2021/2021/07/09/crying-writing-final-good-luck-messages-englands-stars-know/ |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |date=9 July 2021|access-date=9 July 2021 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}{{cbignore}}</ref> In an interview, Saka stated the importance of his father, Yomi, in his footballing career: "He's a massive inspiration for me. From when I was young, he always kept me grounded, kept me humble."<ref>{{cite web |last=Benge |first=James |date=20 September 2019 |title=Ljungberg, Ronaldo and his father – The men who made Saka |url=https://www.football.london/arsenal-fc/players/freddie-ljungberg-cristiano-ronaldo-father-16951058 |access-date=28 January 2021 |website=Football.London |archive-date=12 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200812162324/https://www.football.london/arsenal-fc/players/freddie-ljungberg-cristiano-ronaldo-father-16951058 |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
Having previously played for youth teams of [[Watford F.C.|Watford]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Berrill |first=Lewis |date=9 July 2021 |title=Harry Kane, Bukayo Saka and Jadon Sancho's time at Watford FC |url=https://www.watfordobserver.co.uk/news/19432871.harry-kane-bukayo-saka-jadon-sanchos-time-watford-fc/|url-status=live|access-date=18 July 2021 |newspaper=Watford Observer|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210709163108/https://www.watfordobserver.co.uk/news/19432871.harry-kane-bukayo-saka-jadon-sanchos-time-watford-fc/ |archive-date=9 July 2021}}</ref> Saka joined Arsenal's [[Hale End]] [[Arsenal F.C. Under-21s and Academy|academy]]<ref name="G">{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/meet-bukayo-saka-the-latest-arsenal-academy-star-making-a/1s5io5p2o0qk41kfp30ivme0rh |title=Meet Bukayo Saka: The latest Arsenal academy star making a name for himself |first=Chris |last=Wheatley |website=Goal |publisher=Perform Group |date=20 November 2018 |access-date=29 November 2018 |archive-date=2 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602141701/https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/meet-bukayo-saka-the-latest-arsenal-academy-star-making-a/1s5io5p2o0qk41kfp30ivme0rh |url-status=live }}</ref> at the age of seven.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Why Saka could be a future Arsenal captain |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56726954 |access-date=15 April 2021 |archive-date=15 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210415052747/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56726954 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2020, the [[Arsenal F.C. Under-21s and Academy|Arsenal U16]] coach [[Trevor Bumstead]] said: "Bukayo always stood out in the younger teams. He was a fantastic decisionmaker. He knew when to beat people and when to pass, as well as having brilliant physical attributes and really good character and personality."<ref>{{Cite podcast |title=Episode 13: Former West Ham United and Arsenal Academy Coach Trevor Bumstead |website=Anchor FM |url=https://anchor.fm/downthetunnelwithkb/episodes/Episode-13---Former-West-Ham-United--Arsenal-Academy-Coach---Trevor-Bumstead-egbamj|date=6 July 2020|access-date=14 December 2022}}</ref> Once he turned 17 years old, Saka signed a professional contract with Arsenal and was promoted to the under-23 team.<ref name="G" />

On 29 November 2018, Saka made his [[First team (association football)|first-team]] debut for Arsenal in their [[UEFA Europa League]] match against [[FC Vorskla Poltava|Vorskla Poltava]], coming on as a 68th-minute [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Aaron Ramsey]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Vorskla vs Arsenal |url=https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2018/11/29/europe/uefa-cup/fc-vorskla-poltava/arsenal-fc/2909571/ |website=Soccerway |access-date=29 November 2018 |archive-date=7 September 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200907080535/https://us.soccerway.com/matches/2018/11/29/europe/uefa-cup/fc-vorskla-poltava/arsenal-fc/2909571/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 13 December, Saka made his first full home debut for Arsenal in their Europa League match against [[Qarabağ FK|Qarabağ]].<ref>{{cite web |date=14 December 2018 |title=Bukayo Saka thrilled to make Arsenal debut in Europa League win |url=https://sportsloveme.com/soccer/bukayo-saka-thrilled-to-make-arsenal-debut-in-europa-league-win/ |access-date=4 June 2021 |website=Sports Love Me |archive-date=4 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210604200210/https://sportsloveme.com/soccer/bukayo-saka-thrilled-to-make-arsenal-debut-in-europa-league-win/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 January 2019, Saka made his debut in the [[Premier League]] in a 4–1 win against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] after coming on for [[Alex Iwobi]] in the 83rd minute.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/he-is-very-important-for-us-emery-excited-by-sakas-arsenal/nxfi3kd76zop1soq6vivyqf09 |title=Arsenal news: Emery excited by Saka's Arsenal debut |website=Goal |publisher=Perform Group |access-date=14 December 2018 |archive-date=12 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200812171305/https://www.goal.com/en/news/he-is-very-important-for-us-emery-excited-by-sakas-arsenal/nxfi3kd76zop1soq6vivyqf09 |url-status=live }}</ref> He became the first player born in 2001 to play in a Premier League match.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saka breaks new ground for class of 2001 |date=3 January 2019 |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/964882 |publisher=Premier League |access-date=8 June 2021 |archive-date=30 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210730045638/https://www.premierleague.com/news/964882 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was an unused substitute in the [[2019 UEFA Europa League final]] 4–1 defeat against Chelsea on 29 May, receiving a runners-up medal.<ref>{{Cite web |date=29 May 2019 |title=Chelsea beat Arsenal 4–1 to win Europa League final |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48368406 |access-date=6 August 2019 |website=BBC Sport |archive-date=2 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602144009/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48368406 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===2019–2020: Breakthrough and FA Cup win===
Saka scored his first goal on 19 September, curling a fine effort from long range into the corner away to German team [[Eintracht Frankfurt]] in the [[2019–20 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]. He finished the match with two [[Assist (association football)|assists]] also to his name in a 3–0 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49745913 |title=Arsenal beat Eintracht in opener |work=BBC Sport |access-date=26 December 2020 |archive-date=9 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210309235533/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49745913 |url-status=live }}</ref> Saka was rewarded for his efforts in Germany with his first Premier League start, in a 3–2 home win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]. He then registered an assist for [[Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang]], setting up Arsenal's equaliser in a 1–1 draw at [[Old Trafford]] against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Arsenal hold Man Utd at Old Trafford |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49791610 |access-date=15 February 2021 |archive-date=20 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210120214400/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49791610 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Following injuries to [[Sead Kolašinac]] and [[Kieran Tierney]], Saka began to establish himself as a regular in the Arsenal first team at [[left-back]]. On 27 January 2020, he scored the opening goal in Arsenal's 2–1 [[FA Cup]] fourth-round victory at [[AFC Bournemouth]] after finishing a 22-pass move. He also assisted the second goal, which was scored by [[Eddie Nketiah]]. The goal was later voted goal of the round by [[BBC Sport]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51272216 |title=FA Cup: Arsenal's Bukayo Saka strike voted goal of the fourth round |work=BBC Sport |access-date=29 January 2020 |archive-date=28 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200128120430/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51272216 |url-status=live }}</ref> After a two-week mid-season break, Saka marked his return to action at home to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] with an assist for [[Nicolas Pépé]]'s goal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51431286 |title=Arsenal 4–0 Newcastle: Gunners beat Magpies to end run of draws |date=16 February 2020 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=9 April 2020 |archive-date=27 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201027063736/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51431286 |url-status=live }}</ref> He then set up [[Alexandre Lacazette]] for his ninth assist of the season in a 1–0 win away to [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] in the Europa League.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51533308 |title=Olympiakos 0–1 Arsenal: Alexandre Lacazette helped by team-mates' support, says Mikel Arteta |date=21 February 2020 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=9 April 2020 |archive-date=28 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228054652/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51533308 |url-status=live }}</ref> He then hit double figures for assists that season after crossing in for Nketiah in a thrilling 3–2 home win against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51519246 |title=Arsenal 3–2 Everton: Aubameyang nets twice as Arsenal beat Everton in thriller |date=23 February 2020 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=9 April 2020 |archive-date=5 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201105033713/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51519246 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 1 July 2020, Saka signed a new long-term contract with Arsenal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/bukayo-saka-signs-new-long-term-contract |title=Bukayo Saka signs new long-term contract |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |date=1 July 2020 |access-date=1 July 2020 |archive-date=1 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200701125511/https://www.arsenal.com/news/bukayo-saka-signs-new-long-term-contract |url-status=live }}</ref> Head coach [[Mikel Arteta]] praised Saka and said: "I think he represents every value that this football club stands for. He has come through the academy, and earned his respect with hard work and accountability and you can see the progression that he is having as a player but as well as a person."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/he-represents-every-value-club-stands |title=He represents every value this club stands for |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |date=1 July 2020 |access-date=1 July 2020 |archive-date=26 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201126185941/https://www.arsenal.com/news/he-represents-every-value-club-stands |url-status=live }}</ref> On 4 July 2020, he scored his first Premier League goal for the club against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]], with a half volley beating goalkeeper [[Rui Patrício]], in a 2–0 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52177948 |title=A week I will remember for life – Saka |work=BBC Sport |access-date=4 July 2020 |archive-date=17 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210117215018/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52177948 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was an unused substitute as Arsenal beat [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 2–1 to win their 14th FA Cup.<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Heads Up FA Cup Final: Arsenal 2–1 Chelsea |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2020/aug/01/heads-up-fa-cup-final-arsenal-chelsea-match-report-010820 |publisher=The Football Association |access-date=30 January 2021 |archive-date=25 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210125045206/https://www.thefa.com/news/2020/aug/01/heads-up-fa-cup-final-arsenal-chelsea-match-report-010820 |url-status=live }}</ref> He came third in the vote for the [[Arsenal Player of the Season Award|Arsenal Player of the Season]] award in the 2019–20 season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arsenal Player of the Season: In third place... |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/arsenal-player-season-third-place |access-date=15 February 2021 |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |archive-date=18 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201018112349/https://www.arsenal.com/news/arsenal-player-season-third-place |url-status=live }}</ref>

===2020–2022: Back-to-back Arsenal Player of the Season===
On 29 August 2020, Saka was in the starting line-up and registered an assist for Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang in the [[2020 FA Community Shield]], in which [[2019–20 FA Cup]] winners Arsenal clinched a 5–4 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] victory over [[2019–20 Premier League]] winners [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], after the match finished 1–1 after 90 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Arsenal 1–1 Liverpool (5–4 on penalties) |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2020/aug/29/arsenal-liverpool-mens-fa-community-shield-match-report-290820 |publisher=The Football Association |access-date=30 January 2021 |archive-date=10 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210310001454/https://www.thefa.com/news/2020/aug/29/arsenal-liverpool-mens-fa-community-shield-match-report-290820 |url-status=live }}</ref> Saka opened his account for the [[2020–21 Arsenal F.C. season|2020–21 season]] on 4 October, scoring in a 2–1 victory against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] at the [[Emirates Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Arsenal 2–1 Sheffield United: Gunners extend Blades' point-less start |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54313273 |access-date=4 October 2020 |archive-date=4 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201004152202/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54313273 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 8 November, Saka turned in [[Matt Targett]]'s cross and scored an [[Own goal (association football)|own goal]] in a 3–0 home defeat against Aston Villa.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Arsenal 0–3 Aston Villa: Ollie Watkins hails 'unbelievable' win against boyhood team |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54766713 |access-date=8 November 2020 |archive-date=12 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210212125142/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54766713 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 26 December 2020, Saka scored on his 40th Premier League appearance for Arsenal in a 3–1 home win over Chelsea.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/55373755 |title=Arsenal 3–1 Chelsea |website=BBC Sport |date=26 December 2020 |access-date=26 December 2020 |archive-date=7 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210207223833/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/55373755 |url-status=live }}</ref> Due to his performances in December 2020, he later voted as the Arsenal Player of the Month.<ref>{{cite web |title=🏆 Saka is our December Player of the Month! 😎 |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-our-december-player-month |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |access-date=15 February 2021 |archive-date=1 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210201140222/https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-our-december-player-month |url-status=live }}</ref> He was voted as the Player of the Month again in January 2021, having scored three goals and one assist. His goal against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] was voted as the runner-up of Arsenal's Goal of the Month.<ref>{{cite web |title=🏆 Saka is our Player of the Month... again! |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-our-player-month-again |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |access-date=15 February 2021 |archive-date=7 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210307160041/https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-our-player-month-again |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Kieran Tierney tops January Goal of the Month poll |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/kieran-tierney-tops-january-goal-month-poll |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |access-date=15 February 2021 |archive-date=13 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210213235218/https://www.arsenal.com/news/kieran-tierney-tops-january-goal-month-poll |url-status=live }}</ref> Saka was named Player of the Month for the third time in February after contributing one goal and two assists.<ref>{{cite web |title=🏆🏆🏆 Saka makes it a hat-trick of POM awards! |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-makes-it-hat-trick-pom-awards |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |access-date=15 March 2021 |archive-date=18 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210318223443/https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-makes-it-hat-trick-pom-awards |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 6 March 2021, Saka made his 50th Premier League appearance for Arsenal in a 1–1 away draw at [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]]; he is the second youngest player in club history to reach that milestone.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Xhaka error gifts Burnley point |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56220041 |access-date=6 March 2021 |archive-date=6 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210306143538/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/56220041 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 15 April, Saka scored a goal and helped Arsenal to a 4–0 victory over [[SK Slavia Prague|Slavia Prague]] in the quarter-final of the [[2020–21 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]. After his fine performance, he was named as the Europa League Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Dean |first1=Sam |last2=Zeqiri |first2=Daniel |date=15 April 2021 |title=Impressive Arsenal tear Slavia Prague apart to set up Unai Emery reunion |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2021/04/15/slavia-prague-vs-arsenal-europa-league-quarter-final-live-score/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2021/04/15/slavia-prague-vs-arsenal-europa-league-quarter-final-live-score/ |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|access-date=16 April 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=16 April 2021 |title=Saka bags Europa League award after Slavia Prague display |url=https://www.yardbarker.com/soccer/articles/saka_bags_europa_league_award_after_slavia_prague_display/s1_15968_34651292 |access-date=16 April 2021 |website=Yardbarker |archive-date=16 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210416231256/https://www.yardbarker.com/soccer/articles/saka_bags_europa_league_award_after_slavia_prague_display/s1_15968_34651292 |url-status=live }}</ref> He finished the season with seven goals and seven assists in 46 appearances across all competitions, as he was voted Arsenal Player of the Season,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/arsenal-player-season-first-place |title=Arsenal Player of the Season: In first place... &#124; Player of the season |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |date=4 June 2021 |access-date=2 December 2021 |archive-date=3 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211203041655/https://www.arsenal.com/news/arsenal-player-season-first-place |url-status=live }}</ref> having come in third the previous campaign. He was also named in the shortlist for the PFA Young Player of the Season, eventually won by [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]'s [[Phil Foden]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.premierleague.com/news/2160566 |title=Nominees for 2020/21 Hublot Young Player of the Season |date=2 June 2021 |publisher=Premier League |access-date=2 December 2021 |archive-date=31 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211031051459/https://www.premierleague.com/news/2160566 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Saka scored his first goal of the [[2021–22 Arsenal F.C. season|new campaign]] in a 6–0 [[2021–22 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] second-round win away to West Bromwich Albion at [[The Hawthorns]] in late August.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/58252911 |title=West Brom 0–6 Arsenal: Aubameyang stars as Gunners secure first win of season |website=BBC Sport |date=25 August 2021 |access-date=27 August 2021 |archive-date=26 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221026103842/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/58252911 |url-status=live }}</ref> He scored his first [[2021–22 Premier League|Premier League]] goal of the season in September against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at the Emirates Stadium, whilst also providing an assist for [[Emile Smith Rowe]]'s goal in a 3–1 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/58613174 |title=Arsenal 3–1 Tottenham: Gunners defeat north London rivals at Emirates Stadium |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=25 September 2021 |access-date=28 September 2021 |archive-date=27 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210927204746/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/58613174 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 30 October, Saka made his 100th appearance for Arsenal, marking the occasion with an assist in a 2–0 away win at [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59019332 |title=Leicester City 0–2 Arsenal: Mikel Arteta's side extend unbeaten run with fine victory over Foxes |first=Steve |last=Sutcliffe |website=BBC Sport |date=30 October 2021 |access-date=30 October 2021 |archive-date=30 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211030074805/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/59019332 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 26 December, Saka scored his first brace as Arsenal beat [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] 5–0 at [[Carrow Road]]. In doing so, Saka became the second youngest player, after [[Nicolas Anelka]], to score 10 Premier League goals for Arsenal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12504014/norwich-0-5-arsenal-mikel-artetas-two-year-anniversary-with-gunners-marked-with-thumping-win |title=Norwich 0–5 Arsenal: Mikel Arteta's two-year anniversary with Gunners marked with thumping win |website=Sky Sports |date=26 December 2021 |access-date=7 January 2022 |archive-date=29 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211229103851/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12504014/norwich-0-5-arsenal-mikel-artetas-two-year-anniversary-with-gunners-marked-with-thumping-win |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 19 March 2022, Saka scored Arsenal's 2000th Premier League goal in history, as the Gunners defeated [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] 1–0 away at [[Villa Park]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Aston Villa 0–1 Arsenal: Bukayo Saka secures narrow win for Gunners |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60698102 |website=BBC Sport |date=19 March 2022}}</ref> As a result of his performances during March 2022, which included two goals and an assist, Saka was nominated for the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] award.<ref>{{cite web |title=March 2022's EA SPORTS Player of the Month nominees |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/2540638 |website=Premier League |date=27 March 2022}}</ref> He scored his tenth Premier League goal of the season (for the first time in his career) on 20 April, in a 4–2 away victory against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Chelsea 2–4 Arsenal: Eddie Nketiah scores twice in win for Gunners |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60269088 |website=BBC Sport |date=20 April 2022}}</ref>

Arsenal finished fifth in the Premier League, falling short of [[UEFA Champions League]] qualification for the following season.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Watts |first=Charles |date=6 June 2022 |title=Arsenal season review: A pitiful end to a promising campaign |website=Goal |url=https://www.goal.com/en-au/news/arsenal-season-review-a-pitiful-end-to-a-promising-season/blt533349de65026c2d |access-date=13 June 2022 |archive-date=13 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220613111638/https://www.goal.com/en-au/news/arsenal-season-review-a-pitiful-end-to-a-promising-season/blt533349de65026c2d |url-status=live }}</ref> After finishing the season as the club's top scorer, he was nominated for the [[Premier League Player of the Season]], [[Premier League Young Player of the Season]] and [[PFA Young Player of the Year]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Summerscales |first=Robert |title=Arsenal Duo Make PFA Young Player of the Year Shortlist But Phil Foden Tipped To Retain Award |url=https://www.si.com/fannation/soccer/futbol/news/arsenal-duo-and-phil-foden-on-pfa-young-player-of-the-year-list |access-date=13 June 2022 |website=Futbol on FanNation |date=June 2022 |archive-date=13 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220613111639/https://www.si.com/fannation/soccer/futbol/news/arsenal-duo-and-phil-foden-on-pfa-young-player-of-the-year-list |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Mohamed Salah, Heung-Min Son, Kevin De Bruyne among Premier League player of the season nominees |url=https://uk-sport-web.prod.oceanusorigin.com/football/news/11095/12612067/mohamed-salah-heung-min-son-kevin-de-bruyne-among-premier-league-player-of-the-season-nominees |access-date=13 June 2022 |website=Sky Sports }}{{Dead link|date=June 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Foden named Hublot Young Player of the Season |date=22 May 2022 |url=http://www.premierleague.com/news/2621849 |access-date=13 June 2022 |publisher=Premier League |archive-date=3 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220603195226/https://www.premierleague.com/news/2621849 |url-status=live }}</ref> Saka was named Arsenal's Player of the Season for a second consecutive season, becoming the first person to retain the award since [[Thierry Henry]] won in 2003 and again in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web |date=8 June 2022 |title=Bukayo Saka wins 2021–22 Arsenal Player of the Season |url=https://www.90min.com/posts/bukayo-saka-wins-2021-22-arsenal-player-of-the-season |access-date=13 June 2022 |website=90min.com |archive-date=28 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220928211055/https://www.90min.com/posts/bukayo-saka-wins-2021-22-arsenal-player-of-the-season |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===2022–present: Title challengers===
[[File:RC Lens - Arsenal FC (03-10-2023) 16.jpg|thumb|upright|Saka training with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 2023]]

Saka played a pivotal role for Arsenal during the [[2022–23 Arsenal F.C. season|2022–23 season]], scoring crucial goals and providing assists as Arsenal aimed to win their first Premier League title since [[2003–04 FA Premier League|2003–04]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2023/02/25/leicester-city-vs-arsenal-result-away-day-blues-thing-past-title/|website=The Telegraph|first=John|last=Percy|title=Arsenal limit Leicester to one shot – they are no longer a soft touch|date=25 February 2023|access-date=26 February 2023|archive-date=26 February 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230226005952/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2023/02/25/leicester-city-vs-arsenal-result-away-day-blues-thing-past-title/|url-status=live}}</ref> On 20 August 2022, he made his 100th Premier League appearance in a 3–0 win at Bournemouth, becoming the second youngest Arsenal player to reach that milestone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-and-ramsdale-celebrate-pl-centuries|website=Arsenal F.C.|title=Saka and Ramsdale celebrate PL centuries|date=21 September 2022|access-date=25 February 2023|archive-date=25 February 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230225141646/https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-and-ramsdale-celebrate-pl-centuries|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored first goal of the season in a 3–1 away defeat against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] on 4 September.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester United 3–1 Arsenal: Antony scores on his debut to end Arsenal's winning run |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62704217 |access-date=4 September 2022 |archive-date=19 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230219170722/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62704217 |url-status=live }}</ref> In their next Premier League match on 18 September, Saka would provide two assists for teammates [[William Saliba]] and [[Fábio Vieira (footballer, born 2000)|Fábio Vieira]] in a 3–0 away victory at [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]], a result that would sent Arsenal to the top of the table.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brentford 0–3 Arsenal: Ethan Nwaneri becomes youngest ever Premier League player as Gunners go top |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62866738 |website=BBC Sport |date=18 September 2022}}</ref> In October, Saka would score in three consecutive matches for the first time in his career, with a [[Brace (association football)|brace]] against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] on 9 October, and goals against [[FK Bodø/Glimt|Bodø/Glimt]] in the [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] and [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in the Premier League on 13 October and 16 October, respectively.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Arsenal 3–2 Liverpool: Bukayo Saka double helps Gunners regain top spot |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63106170 |access-date=9 October 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Bodø/Glimt 0–1 Arsenal: Bukayo Saka scores as Gunners near Europa League progression |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63236405 |access-date=13 October 2022 |archive-date=12 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221012232308/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63236405 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Leeds United 0–1 Arsenal: Bukayo Saka scores winning goal |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63189783 |access-date=16 October 2022}}</ref>

On 26 December 2022, Saka scored the equaliser in Arsenal's first match since the conclusion of the World Cup, a 3–1 win over [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. He scored again in their next match against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], a 4–2 away victory.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Arsenal 3–1 West Ham United: Premier League leaders extend advantage to seven points |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64022710 |access-date=26 December 2022 |archive-date=26 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221226225131/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64022710 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Brighton & Hove Albion 2–4 Arsenal: Gunners extend lead to seven points |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64083699 |website=BBC Sport |date=31 December 2022}}</ref> On 15 January 2023, Saka provided the assist for [[Martin Ødegaard]]'s goal against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] as Arsenal sealed their first away league win against their [[North London derby|rivals]] since 2014.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Tottenham Hotspur 0–2 Arsenal: Hugo Lloris own goal and Martin Ødegaard strike sends Gunners eight clear |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64201166 |access-date=15 January 2023 |archive-date=25 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230125091931/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64201166 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Hytner |first=David |date=2023-01-15 |title=Arsenal march on as Ødegaard applies finishing touch for win at Tottenham |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/jan/15/tottenham-hotspur-arsenal-premier-league-match-report |access-date=2023-09-25 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=15 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230115214056/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/jan/15/tottenham-hotspur-arsenal-premier-league-match-report |url-status=live }}</ref> A week later on 22 January, Saka scored from long-range in an eventual 3–2 home win over Manchester United.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Late Nketiah goal hands Arsenal win over Man Utd |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64279776 |access-date=25 September 2023 |archive-date=22 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230122190512/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64279776 |url-status=live }}</ref> This goal was later voted as Arsenal's Goal of the Month for January 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-wins-januarys-goal-month-vote|website=Arsenal F.C.|title=Saka wins January's Goal of the Month vote|date=14 February 2023|access-date=25 February 2023|archive-date=14 February 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230214200355/https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-wins-januarys-goal-month-vote|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 13 March 2023, Saka received the Men's Young Player of the Year award at the 2023 London Football Awards.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-09-27 |title=Quartet honoured at London Football Awards |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/quartet-honoured-london-football-awards |access-date=2023-09-25 |website=Quartet honoured at London Football Awards |archive-date=14 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230314221711/https://www.arsenal.com/news/quartet-honoured-london-football-awards |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=London Football Awards – The Winners |url=https://londonfootballawards.org/the-winners/ |access-date=25 September 2023 |archive-date=20 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201020032150/https://londonfootballawards.org/the-winners/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He was then awarded the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] award for March 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Saka wins first EA SPORTS Player of the Month award |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/3124438 |access-date=25 September 2023 |website=www.premierleague.com |date=31 March 2023 |archive-date=31 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230331101024/https://www.premierleague.com/news/3124438 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 23 May, Saka signed a long-term contract with Arsenal, committing him to the club until 2027.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Media |first1=Arsenal |title=Bukayo Saka signs new contract |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/bukayo-saka-signs-new-contract |website=Arsenal F.C. |access-date=23 May 2023 |date=23 May 2023 |archive-date=23 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230523141316/https://www.arsenal.com/news/bukayo-saka-signs-new-contract |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Bukayo Saka: Arsenal winger signs new long-term contract with Mikel Arteta's Gunners amid stellar season |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12877165/bukayo-saka-arsenal-winger-signs-new-long-term-contract-with-mikel-artetas-gunners-amid-stellar-season |access-date=25 September 2023 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref> At the end of the season, he was nominated for the Premier League Player of the Season, Premier League Young Player of the Season, and [[FWA Footballer of the Year]] awards.<ref>{{Cite web |title=2022/23 EA SPORTS Player of the Season shortlist |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/3345789 |access-date=2023-09-25 |website=www.premierleague.com |date=18 May 2023 |archive-date=10 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230610043039/https://www.premierleague.com/news/3345789 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=2022/23 Hublot Young Player of the Season contenders |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/3345791 |access-date=2023-09-25 |website=www.premierleague.com |date=18 May 2023 |archive-date=18 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230518152232/https://www.premierleague.com/news/3345791 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Awards – Football Writers' Association |url=https://footballwriters.co.uk/awards/ |access-date=2023-09-25}}</ref> Saka was named the PFA Young Player of the Year for the 2022–23 season.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-09-27 |title=Saka wins 22/23 PFA Young Player of the Year award |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-wins-2223-pfa-young-player-year-award |access-date=2023-09-25 |website=Saka wins 22/23 PFA Young Player of the Year award |archive-date=6 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230906222118/https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-wins-2223-pfa-young-player-year-award |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 12 August 2023, Saka's goal helped seal a 2–1 win over [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] in Arsenal's first match of the [[2023–24 Premier League|2023–24 Premier League season]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Superb Saka strike helps Arsenal to win over Forest |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66413654 |access-date=2023-09-25 |archive-date=13 August 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230813013445/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66413654 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 26 August, Saka made his 83rd consecutive Premier League appearance for Arsenal against Fulham, which set a club record.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/aug/25/bukayo-saka-nothing-worth-having-is-easy-its-about-how-much-you-want-it-arsenal |title=Bukayo Saka: 'Nothing worth having is easy. It's about how much you want it' |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=26 August 2023 |access-date=26 August 2023}}</ref> On 20 September, he scored his first Champions League goal and provided an assist in a 4–0 win over [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]] on his debut in the competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66857208 |title=Arsenal 4–0 PSV Eindhoven |publisher=BBC Sport |date=20 September 2023 |access-date=20 September 2023 |archive-date=21 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230921005052/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66857208 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 28 October, Saka [[captain (association football)|captained]] Arsenal for the first time in a 5–0 home win against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-leading-boys-out-was-unbelievable|title=Saka – 'Leading the boys out was unbelievable'|date=28 October 2023|publisher=Arsenal F.C.}}</ref> He made his 200th appearance for the club on 5 December 2023 in a 4–3 win over [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] at [[Kenilworth Road]], becoming the fourth youngest Arsenal player to reach the milestone.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.planetfootball.com/quick-reads/comparing-bukayo-saka-arsenal-record-200-matches-messi-ronaldo|title=Comparing Bukayo Saka's Arsenal record after 200 matches with Messi & Ronaldo|first=Ben|last=Stewart|date=6 December 2023|website=Planet Football}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-reach-200-arsenal-appearances|title=Saka to reach 200 Arsenal appearances|date=9 December 2023|website=Saka to reach 200 Arsenal appearances|access-date=8 December 2023|archive-date=8 December 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231208153923/https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-reach-200-arsenal-appearances|url-status=live}}</ref> On 11 February 2024, Saka surpassed 50 goals for Arsenal with a brace in a 6–0 away win over West Ham, becoming the youngest Arsenal player to do so in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13071635/bukayo-saka-reaches-half-century-for-arsenal-with-more-goals-and-assists-than-cristiano-ronaldo-in-first-210-games | title=Bukayo Saka reaches half-century for Arsenal with more goals and assists than Cristiano Ronaldo in first 210 games | work=Sky Sports | access-date=20 February 2024 | archive-date=20 February 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240220085835/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13071635/bukayo-saka-reaches-half-century-for-arsenal-with-more-goals-and-assists-than-cristiano-ronaldo-in-first-210-games | url-status=live }}</ref>

On 4 October 2025, Saka made his 200th Premier League appearance for Arsenal in a 2–0 win over West Ham United, scoring a penalty — his 55th league goal and 100th goal involvement for the club in the competition.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Saka hits 100 goal involvements in 200 PL games |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-hits-100-goal-involvements-200-pl-games |website=Arsenal.com |access-date=4 October 2025}}</ref> On 19 February 2026, he signed a new long-term contract with the club, reportedly until 2031.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/bukayo-saka-signs-new-long-term-contract-46329922 |title=Bukayo Saka signs new long-term contract |publisher=Arsenal F.C. |date=19 February 2026 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Mokbel |first=Sami |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c4gje501g51o |title=Arsenal make Saka best-paid player with new deal |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 February 2026 }}</ref> On 4 March 2026, he made his 300th appearance for Arsenal, scoring the winner in a 1–0 victory away to [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Rogers |first=Jonathon |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-set-make-300th-arsenal-appearance|title=Saka set to make 300th Arsenal appearance|publisher=Arsenal F.C. |date=4 March 2026}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/soccer/arid-41804411.html|title=Saka's early goal sends Arsenal seven points clear in the title race|first=Chris|last=Hatherall|date=4 March 2026|website=Irish Examiner}}</ref> Later that year, on 5 May, he netted the goal in a 1–0 victory over [[Atlético Madrid]] in the [[2025–26 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|Champions League semi-final]] second leg, securing his club's place in the [[2026 UEFA Champions League final|final]] after 20 years by winning 2–1 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20260505-saka-ends-arsenal-s-20-year-wait-to-reach-champions-league-final |title=Saka ends Arsenal's 20-year wait to reach Champions League final |publisher=France 24 |date=5 May 2026 }}</ref> A few weeks later, on 18 May, he registered his 50th league assist from a corner in a 1–0 victory over Burnley, becoming the third player in the club's history to reach that milestone of goals and assists after [[Thierry Henry]] and [[Dennis Bergkamp]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Knapton |first=Ben |url=https://www.sportsmole.co.uk/football/arsenal/title-race/news/saka-emulates-henry-as-arsenal-equal-two-pl-records-in-burnley-success_597793.html |title=Arsenal equal two Premier League records as Bukayo Saka emulates Thierry Henry in Burnley victory |publisher=Sports Mole |date=18 May 2026 }}</ref> On the following day, Saka won his first Premier League title after Manchester City failed to beat Bournemouth, handing Arsenal their first Premier League title in 22 years.

==International career==
===Youth career===
Saka made his debut for the [[England national under-16 football team|England national under-16 team]] on 24 August 2016 as a substitute in a 3–1 away win over [[Romania national under-16 football team|Romania]] in a [[Friendly (association football)|friendly]].<ref name="EnglandU16">{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU16pg4.html |title=Match Results Under 16: 2010–2020 |website=England Football Online |date=2 March 2023 |access-date=30 September 2023 |archive-date=14 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231114230714/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU16pg4.html |url-status=live }}</ref> He made his first start two days later in a 2–1 defeat to the same opposition in another friendly, in which he scored.<ref name="EnglandU16"/> Saka was part of the squad for the 2017 [[UEFA Under-16 Development Tournament]], making two appearances as England finished the tournament as runners-up.<ref name="EnglandU16"/> He finished his under-16 career with six appearances and one goal from 2016 to 2017.<ref name="EnglandU16"/>

His first involvement with the [[England national under-17 football team|England under-17 team]] came in the 2017 FA International Tournament, making his debut on 18 August 2017 in their opening match, a 3–2 home win over [[Turkey national under-17 football team|Turkey]], in which he scored.<ref name="EnglandU17">{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU17pg2.html |title=Match Results Under 17: 2010–2020 |website=England Football Online |date=28 February 2023 |access-date=30 September 2023 |archive-date=6 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230606060236/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU17pg2.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Saka made one more appearance at the tournament, which England finished as runners-up.<ref name="EnglandU17"/> He was part of the team for the 2018 Torneio Internacional do Algarve, making two appearances as England ranked in third place.<ref name="EnglandU17"/> Saka was named in the team for the [[2018 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] in England, and appeared in all five of the team's matches at the tournament.<ref name="EnglandU17"/> England were eliminated 6–5 on a penalty shoot-out by the [[Netherlands national under-17 football team|Netherlands]] in the semi-final after a 0–0 [[Extra time (association football)|extra-time]] draw, although Saka scored his [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] in the shoot-out.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/under17/match/2024318--england-vs-netherlands/events/ |title=England 0–0 Netherlands: Updates |publisher=UEFA |access-date=30 September 2023 |archive-date=30 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230930182251/https://www.uefa.com/under17/match/2024318--england-vs-netherlands/events/ |url-status=live }}</ref> He made nine appearances for the under-17s, scoring once, from 2017 to 2018.<ref name="EnglandU17"/>

Saka was part of the [[England national under-18 football team|England under-18 team]] for the 2018 Limoges Tournament in France, making his debut in England's opening match, a 3–0 win over the Netherlands on 5 September 2018.<ref name="EnglandU18">{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU18pg7.html |title=Match Results Under 18: 2010–2020 |website=England Football Online |date=1 March 2023 |access-date=30 September 2023}}</ref> He scored the winning goal with a penalty in England's 2–1 win over [[France national under-18 football team|France]] on 9 September, which saw England win the tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2018/sep/10/france-england-u18s-report-100918 |title=England U18s beat hosts France to seal Limoges title with three wins from three games |publisher=The Football Association |date=10 September 2018 |access-date=30 September 2023}}</ref> England won their three matches at the tournament, with Saka appearing in each match.<ref name="EnglandU18"/> He went on to finish his under-18 career with one goal from five appearances, all of which came in 2018.<ref name="EnglandU18"/>

On 14 November 2018, Saka scored on his debut for the [[England national under-19 football team|England under-19 team]] in a 4–0 win over [[Moldova national under-19 football team|Moldova]] in a [[2019 UEFA European Under-19 Championship qualification#Qualifying round|2019 UEFA European Under-19 Championship first qualifying round]] match in Turkey, which he entered as an 82nd-minute substitute.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2018/nov/14/england-u19s-moldova-report-141118 |title=Young Lions kick-off U19 Euro qualifiers in Turkey with a 4–0 win over Moldova |publisher=The Football Association |date=14 November 2018 |access-date=30 September 2023}}</ref> He made his first start at this level on 20 March 2019, in a 4–1 home win over the [[Czech Republic national under-19 football team|Czech Republic]] in a [[2019 UEFA European Under-19 Championship qualification#Elite round|2019 European Under-19 Championship elite qualifying round]] match.<ref name="EnglandU19">{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU19pg2.html |title=Match Results Under 19: 2010–2019 |website=England Football Online |date=22 June 2021 |access-date=30 September 2023 |archive-date=10 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110010030/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/matchrsl/MatchRslTmU19pg2.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Saka scored twice in the match, in the 11th and 56th minute.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2019/mar/20/england-u19s-v-czech-republic-report-200319 |title=Young Lions make a winning start to their U19 Euro qualifiers at St. George's Park |publisher=The Football Association |first=Andy |last=Walker |date=20 March 2019 |access-date=30 September 2023}}</ref> He made 10 appearances for the under-19s, scoring four goals, from 2018 to 2019.<ref name="EnglandU19"/>

===Senior career===
[[File:Bukayo Saka.jpg|thumb|upright|Saka playing for [[England national football team|England]] at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]]]

On 4 September 2020, Saka made his only appearance for the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21 team]] when starting a 6–0 victory away to [[Kosovo national under-21 football team|Kosovo]] in [[2021 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU21pg5.html |title=Match Results Under 21: 2020–30 |website=England Football Online |date=13 September 2023 |access-date=30 September 2023 |archive-date=14 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231114231110/http://www.englandfootballonline.com/MatchRsl/MatchRslTmU21pg5.html |url-status=live }}</ref> On 1 October, Saka was called up to the [[England national football team|England senior]] squad for the first time,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54372190 |title=England squad: Dominic Calvert-Lewin called up but Mason Greenwood and Phil Foden left out |website=BBC Sport |date=1 October 2020 |access-date=2 October 2020 |archive-date=11 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210111061135/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54372190 |url-status=live }}</ref> and made his international debut as one of the starters in a 3–0 victory over [[Wales national football team|Wales]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54366319 |title=England 3–0 Wales |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=8 October 2020 |access-date=10 October 2020 |archive-date=6 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201206024951/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54366319 |url-status=live }}</ref> Having played four times for England, Saka is now tied to England internationally and can no longer represent [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Price |first=Steve |title=FIFA Eligibility Rule Change Offers World Cup Hopes For 'One-Cap Wonders' |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/steveprice/2020/09/19/fifa-eligibility-rule-change-offers-world-cup-hopes-for-one-cap-wonders/ |access-date=3 December 2020 |website=Forbes |archive-date=8 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201108171626/https://www.forbes.com/sites/steveprice/2020/09/19/fifa-eligibility-rule-change-offers-world-cup-hopes-for-one-cap-wonders/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Saka was named in the 26-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2020]]. On 2 June, in a friendly against [[Austria national football team|Austria]], Saka scored his first senior international goal, the only goal in a 1–0 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57250378 |title=England 1–0 Austria: Bukayo Saka seals win with first international goal |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=2 June 2021 |access-date=2 June 2021 |archive-date=19 November 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211119075509/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57250378 |url-status=live }}</ref> He started in England's third [[UEFA Euro 2020 Group D|Euro 2020 group stage]] match on 22 June against the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]], and was named the [[Player of the match|man of the match]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/euro-2020/2021/gareth-southgate-definitely-more-to-come-from-england-after-securing-last-16-place-at-euro-2020_sto8386077/story.shtml |title=Euro 2020 – 'More to come from us' – Gareth Southgate praises England and 'fabulous' Bukayo Saka |date=22 June 2021 |website=Eurosport |access-date=26 June 2021 |archive-date=29 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230629094728/https://www.eurosport.com/geoblocking.shtml |url-status=live }}</ref> On 11 July, in the [[UEFA Euro 2020 final|tournament final]] against [[Italy national football team|Italy]], Saka was brought on as a substitute for [[Kieran Trippier]]. Following extra time, Saka was chosen to take the team's fifth penalty during the subsequent penalty shoot-out, which was his first penalty kick at senior level.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wallace |first=Sam |date=12 July 2021 |title=Bukayo Saka is a teenager who had never taken a penalty – so why was he asked to do it now? |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/euro-2021/2021/07/11/bukayo-saka-teenager-had-never-taken-penalty-asked-do-now/ |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/archive/20220111/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/euro-2021/2021/07/11/bukayo-saka-teenager-had-never-taken-penalty-asked-do-now/ |archive-date=11 January 2022 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live|access-date=12 July 2021}}{{cbignore}}</ref> Saka's effort was saved by goalkeeper [[Gianluigi Donnarumma]] and, as a result, Italy won the shoot-out and the tournament.<ref>{{Cite news |title=England lose shootout in Euro 2020 final |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51198762 |access-date=11 July 2021 |archive-date=11 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210711170405/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51198762 |url-status=live }}</ref> Saka faced racist abuse online after missing the penalty.<ref>{{cite web |date=12 July 2021 |title=England 'disgusted' by racism aimed at players |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/england-eng/story/4431389/england-fa-condemn-racist-abuse-aimed-at-rashfordsakasancho-after-euro-shootout-loss |access-date=12 July 2021 |publisher=ESPN |archive-date=12 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210712024531/https://www.espn.com/soccer/england-eng/story/4431389/england-fa-condemn-racist-abuse-aimed-at-rashfordsakasancho-after-euro-shootout-loss |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=PM & FA condemn racist abuse of players |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57800431 |access-date=12 July 2021 |archive-date=12 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210712011351/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57800431 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 15 July, Saka said that he "knew instantly the kind of hate" he was going to receive after his penalty was saved, adding: "... and that is a sad reality that your powerful platforms are not doing enough to stop these messages".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57855251 |title=Bukayo Saka 'knew instantly of hate' he would receive after England defeat |website=BBC Sport |date=15 July 2021 |access-date=17 July 2021 |archive-date=16 July 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210716075453/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/57855251 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 23 September 2022, Saka was named [[The FA England Awards|England Men's Player of the Year]] for the 2021–22 season ahead of [[Declan Rice]] and [[Harry Kane]], becoming the first Arsenal player to win the honour.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2022/Sep/23/bukayo-saka-named-england-mens-senior-poty-for-2022-20222309 |title=Bukayo Saka wins England men's POTY award for 2022 |publisher=The Football Association |date=23 September 2022 |access-date=23 September 2022 |archive-date=23 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220923135630/https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2022/Sep/23/bukayo-saka-named-england-mens-senior-poty-for-2022-20222309 |url-status=live }}</ref> Saka was named in England's 26-man squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63585869 |title=World Cup 2022: England squad features Maddison, Rashford and Wilson |website=BBC Sport |date=10 November 2022 |access-date=10 November 2022 |archive-date=10 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221110140535/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63585869 |url-status=live }}</ref> He scored twice in a 6–2 victory over [[Iran national football team|Iran]] in England's opening match at the tournament<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63603382 |title=England 6–2 Iran |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=21 November 2022 |access-date=21 November 2022 |archive-date=27 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221127105410/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63603382 |url-status=live }}</ref> and once in England's 3–0 defeat of [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Round of 16|round of 16]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-shines-again-england-reach-quarter-finals|title=Saka shines again as England reach quarter-finals|date=4 December 2022|access-date=25 March 2023|website=Arsenal F.C.|archive-date=29 January 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230129125034/https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-shines-again-england-reach-quarter-finals|url-status=live}}</ref> On 10 December, Saka started in England's 2–1 quarter-final defeat to [[France national football team|France]], and was named the team's man of the match by BBC Sport and ''[[L'Équipe]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63930469|title=World Cup: Bukayo Saka rated best player as England lose to France|date=10 December 2022|access-date=25 March 2023|website=BBC|archive-date=25 March 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230325121927/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63930469|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Article/Les-notes-d-angleterre-france-un-duel-kane-lloris-au-sommet/1369501|title=Les notes d'Angleterre-France : un duel Kane-Lloris au sommet |language=fr |date=11 December 2022|access-date=25 March 2022|website=L'Équipe|archive-date=10 December 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221210214947/https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Article/Les-notes-d-angleterre-france-un-duel-kane-lloris-au-sommet/1369501|url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 June 2023, he scored his first career [[Hat-trick (association football)|hat-trick]] in a 7–0 home win over [[North Macedonia national football team|North Macedonia]] in [[UEFA Euro 2024 qualifying|Euro 2024 qualifying]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=McNulty |first1=Phil |title=England 7–0 North Macedonia: Bukayo Saka scores first career hat-trick in emphatic victory |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65874634 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=20 June 2023 |date=19 June 2023 |archive-date=19 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230619221620/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65874634 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 5 September 2023, Saka was named England Men's Player of the Year for a second successive season having scored seven goals in ten internationals during the 2022–23 season.<ref name=poy>{{cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Andy |title=Bukayo Saka named as England Player of the Year for 2023 |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/Sep/05/bukayo-saka-wins-england-mens-player-of-the-year-award-for-2023-20230509 |website=England Football |access-date=6 September 2023 |date=5 September 2023 |archive-date=5 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230905211805/https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/Sep/05/bukayo-saka-wins-england-mens-player-of-the-year-award-for-2023-20230509 |url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2024, Saka was named in England's 26-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cv22menk7dno |title=Eze & Wharton named in England squad for Euro 2024 |website=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2024 |access-date=6 June 2024 |archive-date=7 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240607013843/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cv22menk7dno |url-status=live }}</ref> In the team's opening match against [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]], he started on the right of the attack and provided the cross for [[Jude Bellingham]] goal to give England a 1–0 win that put them top of [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group C|Group C]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cz992dxd4xwt#Line-ups|title=Hungary 1–3 Switzerland LIVE: UEFA Euro 2024 – score, updates & reaction|website=BBC Sport|access-date=17 June 2024|archive-date=17 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240617013156/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cz992dxd4xwt#Line-ups|url-status=live}}</ref> In the quarter-final match against [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], he was awarded player of the match, scoring the equaliser in a 1–1 draw and also scoring in the subsequent penalty shootout victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028f-1b4e143fd946-8d1c55ab8bed-1000--england-1-1-switzerland-aet-5-3-pens-pickford-and-saka-l/ |title=England 1–1 Switzerland (aet, 5–3 pens): Pickford and Saka lead Southgate's men into semis |publisher=UEFA |date=6 July 2024 |access-date=7 July 2024 |archive-date=7 July 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240707045212/https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028f-1b4e143fd946-8d1c55ab8bed-1000--england-1-1-switzerland-aet-5-3-pens-pickford-and-saka-l/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Player profile==
===Style of play===
Considered one of the best wingers in the world,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/ranked-best-right-wingers-in-the-world |title=Ranked: The Best Right-Wingers In The World |website=FourFourTwo |date=June 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/45179056/2025-fc-100-salah-best-wingers-mens-soccer |title=2025 FC 100: Salah among best wingers in men's soccer |website=ESPN |date=2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/the-best-right-wingers-in-world-soccer-ranked |title=The Best Right-Wingers in World Soccer Ranked |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=July 2025}}</ref> Saka is a skilled dribbler, creative player and prolific goalscorer.<ref name=pfsa>{{Cite web |date=2024-01-02 |title=The Best Footballers in the World 2024 |url=https://thepfsa.co.uk/the-best-footballers-in-the-world/ |access-date=2024-10-27 |website=The PFSA |language=en-GB}}</ref> Predominantly a [[right winger]], Saka uses his pace, dribbling ability, and strength to beat defenders. Naturally left-footed, he is known for cutting inside to score long-range, curled efforts, or delivering crosses. His proficiency with his right foot also makes him a threat on the byline. Despite primarily playing on the right, Saka has demonstrated versatility, featuring as a left winger, left wing-back, and even left-back throughout his Arsenal and England career.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-how-left-back-will-improve-me-winger |title=Saka: How left-back will improve me as a winger |website=Arsenal.com |date=17 February 2020 |access-date=20 September 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arsenal.com/news/saka-how-ive-adapted-playing-wing-back |title=Saka: How I've adapted to playing wing-back |website=Arsenal.com |date=20 September 2018 |access-date=20 September 2025}}</ref>

He has drawn comparisons to [[Arjen Robben]], with former Premier League defender [[Glen Johnson]] highlighting his pace, goal threat, and work rate.{{citation needed|date=December 2025}}

===Reception===
Former Arsenal midfielder [[Paul Merson]] described Saka as a "big moment" player, stating that he consistently delivers in crucial matches.<ref>{{cite web |title=Paul Merson admits 'shock' at Arsenal transfer as he poses Bukayo Saka question |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/arsenal-bukayo-saka-paul-merson-29575179 |work=Daily Mirror |date=19 July 2025}}</ref>{{better source needed|reason=tabloid|date=December 2025}}

Saka is known by the nickname "Little Chilli", given to him by then-captain [[Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang]], who described him as having "so much energy, so much power, and being quite small."<ref>{{cite web |last=Olley |first=James |title=Arsenal's 'little chilli' Bukayo Saka hails impact of Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang on career |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/37618040/arsenal-little-chilli-bukayo-saka-hails-impact-pierre-emerick-aubameyang-career |website=ESPN.co.uk |date=11 June 2021 |access-date=25 September 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Thomas |first=Josh |title=Aubameyang explains unusual nickname for Arsenal prodigy Saka |url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/aubameyang-explains-unusual-nickname-for-arsenal-prodigy-saka/oor33zb5q51g1ck46q3m1pcrz |website=Goal.com |access-date=25 September 2025}}</ref> He is also referred to as "Starboy".<ref>{{cite web |last=The Athletic |title=Bukayo Saka: "Starboy," England |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5628752/2024/07/14/bukayo-saka-starboy-england/ |website=The New York Times / The Athletic |date=15 July 2024 |access-date=25 September 2025}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Saka's favourite footballer is Thierry Henry and he cites [[Alexis Sánchez]] as an influence, saying he even tried to copy Sánchez's boots when he was an academy player. Among past teammates, Saka said [[David Luiz]] helped him the most in his career, saying "he went out of his way" to help a lot of Arsenal youngsters "on and off the pitch".<ref>{{Cite web|title=Bukayo Saka Reveals The Teammate Who Helped Him The Most {{!}} FAQs| date=26 November 2021 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rFALiGb81RM|via=YouTube|access-date=2 December 2021|archive-date=2 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211202005359/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rFALiGb81RM|url-status=live}}</ref> Saka is a practising [[Christian]] and has said that he reads the Bible every night.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Fowle |first=Emma |title='I hold onto God's promises' – the Christian faith of Bukayo Saka |url=https://www.premierchristianity.com/i-hold-onto-gods-promises-the-christian-faith-of-bukayo-saka/5250.article |access-date=13 May 2022 |website=Premier Christianity |archive-date=20 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220520195026/https://www.premierchristianity.com/i-hold-onto-gods-promises-the-christian-faith-of-bukayo-saka/5250.article |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Thompson |first=Scott |date=7 December 2022 |title=England's Bukayo Saka using 'presence of God' to shine in first World Cup. |url=https://www.foxnews.com/sports/englands-bukayo-saka-using-presence-god-shine-first-world-cup.amp |url-status=live |access-date=14 January 2023 |website=Fox News |archive-date=14 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230114203909/https://www.foxnews.com/sports/englands-bukayo-saka-using-presence-god-shine-first-world-cup.amp }}</ref> In March 2024, Saka launched his own range of [[Piri piri|peri-peri]] sauce named 'PERi-PERi Saka' at the [[Nando's]] restaurant chain.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Banerjee |first=Ritabrata |date=19 March 2024 |title=Bukayo Saka creates his own Nando's sauce as Arsenal star's 'PERi-PERi Saka' to be available in every restaurant in England |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/lists/bukayo-saka-nando-s-sauce-peri-peri-saka-to-be-available-in-every-restaurant-england/blt83825cbdb67fd353#cs9f6015190a5de41a |access-date=21 March 2024 |website=Goal |archive-date=21 March 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240321132842/https://www.goal.com/en-gb/lists/bukayo-saka-nando-s-sauce-peri-peri-saka-to-be-available-in-every-restaurant-england/blt83825cbdb67fd353#cs9f6015190a5de41a |url-status=live }}</ref> Saka is in a relationship with Tolami Benson, and they prefer to keep their relationship largely private.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Phillip |first=Riann |date=2024-06-17 |title=Who Is Tolami Benson, The Woman Reviving WAG Fever At The Euros? |url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/who-is-tolami-benson |access-date=2025-07-11 |website=British Vogue |language=en-GB}}</ref>

